<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Audit costs 'lower in efficient companies'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies with a high economic and managerial performance pay lower audit
fees, says a report published today and based on analysis of nearly 700 sets
of accounts.
The annual report, by JDH Consultants, finds that in many cases companies
with a low performance have been charged 50 per cent to 100 per cent more
for an audit.
The University of Glasgow's accounting and finance department is studying
the results. Professor Neil Garrod said: 'This research is extremely well
founded.'
Two reasons had been put forward for the relationship. The first suggested
that high-performing companies got value for money. 'It may be that the best
managers are the best negotiators,' he said.
Mr Dennis Henry, managing director of JDH Consultants, said: 'The other
obvious possibility is that the high-performing companies have accounts
which are more easily audited. If this is the case then another question
must be posed: 'Is there a connection between accounts which are easily
audited and company performance?' This could fit in with what appears to be
the case, that it takes 50 per cent to 100 per cent longer to audit accounts
of the less well-performing companies.'
Prof Garrod is interested in the possibility that good internal audit
practices have a clear impact on performance and keeping down audit fees.
Performance criteria were used by the consultants and matched against audit
fees to find a correlation. The criteria included return on assets, profit
margin and the value added by employees.
Another result of the analysis is that in those cases where the auditor
changed the fees charged had been reduced by an average 28.25 per cent. This
helps explain the increasing tendency for audits to be put out to tender.
In general, fees charged on accounts before October 6 this year rose 0.58
per cent - with audit fees rising 2.25 per cent while non-audit fees fell
1.77 per cent. This again illustrates a highly competitive sector.
The JDH analysis found, as it has done in recent years, a correlation
between the size of companies and audit fee charged and the sector and the
fee charged - but with big variations.
Some companies of the same size, in the same sector, were paying 10 times as
much for audit. Mr Henry said: 'Whilst I might accept a ratio of 2:1 or 3:1
as being reasonable, 10:1 takes a bit of understanding.'
On fees for companies of different size he added: 'The small guys pay more
and the big boys pay less. It takes a lot of big increases to the small ones
to make up for some reductions to the big ones. The big auditors have the
smaller companies over a barrel.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
