<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Booklet on jobless figures attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kevin Barron, shadow employment minister, yesterday attacked a Department
of Employment booklet on how unemployment is measured as 'misleading and
wasteful'.
The pamphlet, which was sent to labour market statistics users last Friday,
included descriptions of the two surveys used by the department, the monthly
count of those claiming unemployment-related benefits (the claimant count)
and the quarterly survey of households (the labour force survey).
In the past year the Labour party has often criticised the government for
its use of the claimant count as its headline figure. The Department of
Employment said it issued the booklet to clarify its use of both forms of
measure.
But Mr Barron said the booklet was inaccurate because it said there had been
nine changes to the rules and procedures of benefit payments since 1979
which warranted adjustments to the counts.
The minister said Labour's employment team had gone through data from the
House of Commons library and identified 29 changes to the rules and
procedures resulting in a reduction to the headline unemployment figure of
nearly 700,000.
The Department of Employment rebutted Mr Barron's assertion about the 29
changes. It said all but nine of them were 'not significant enough to
justify a recasting of the back-series' of figures.
</TEXT>
