<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Maxwell schemes offered up to Pounds 300m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A group of investment banks and former professional advisers to pension
schemes controlled by the late Robert Maxwell has offered to pay between
Pounds 200m and Pounds 300m in a 'global settlement' of all outstanding
claims.
Yesterday trustees of the schemes and their advisers met Sir Peter Webster
of the Maxwell Pensioners Trust who told them of the offers he had received.
Sir Peter had set a deadline of November 4 by which time all offers of
settlement had to be made. Those which did not make 'credible' offers could
expect legal proceedings against them to continue.
Trustees had hoped for an offer closer to the Pounds 448m estimated to have
disappeared from the schemes.
Meanwhile, it has emerged that Mirror Group Pension Scheme, the only one of
the former Maxwell schemes which still has a solvent sponsor, could scupper
the global settlement if an agreement is not reached with the Department of
Social Security.
The issue is whether the department is prepared to waive the requirement
that each scheme repay the government for the portion of State Earnings
Related Pensions (Serps) which has been paid through tax receipts since
1992.
The department said yesterday: 'We can defer the state scheme premiums but
we are not going to write them off.'
In order to allow the Maxwell pensioners to receive Serps, each scheme would
have had to pay a premium to the government. The aggregate value of these
premiums is Pounds 115m.
In October 1992 the government said it would defer collection of the
premiums in order to allow time for recovery of assets from other sources.
It is understood, however, that the department intends to reclaim these
payments if the schemes recover assets.
</TEXT>
