<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Venables company liquidator removed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The liquidator of Edennote, the insolvent company of former Tottenham
Hotspur chief executive Mr Terry Venables, was removed from his post by a
High Court judge yesterday because he sold the company's only substantial
asset to Mr Venables without inviting offers from other creditors.
Mr Stephen Ryman was removed as a result of action taken by Mr Alan Sugar,
Tottenham Hotspur chairman, and his holding company Amshold, major creditors
of Edennote.
Mr Ryman had assigned to Mr Venables Edennote's interest in a pending Pounds
1m damages claim launched by Mr Venables and Edennote against Tottenham. The
claim concerned Mr Venables' allegedly wrongful dismissal as Spurs chief
executive and team manager in May last year.
Mr Venables paid Pounds 7,000 for the assignment and pledged to pay the
liquidator 10 per cent of any net proceeds he recovered in the action. The
judge, Sir John Vinelott, cancelled the assignment and said Mr Ryman should
have approached Tottenham to see if it would offer a better deal. The judge
stressed that no attack had been made on Mr Ryman's integrity and good
faith.
</TEXT>
