<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Severn Bridge tolls to rise 9%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tolls to cross the Severn bridge on the M4 motorway between England and
Wales will rise almost 9 per cent in the new year, taking the cost for a car
to Pounds 3.70 from Pounds 3.40, Roland Adburgham writes.
The announcement yesterday by Severn River Crossing, the consortium which
operates the bridge, provoked an angry reaction from motoring and haulage
organisations. Tolls rose nearly 10 per cent in January this year.
Under a formula set by the Severn Bridges Act, the coming increase will be
the last allowed above the rate of inflation. The tolls, which are charged
in the westbound direction only, are used to maintain the bridge and finance
the Pounds 300m second Severn bridge, under construction three miles
downstream.
The toll for a heavy truck will rise by Pounds 1 to Pounds 11.10, prompting
fears that this will cause a further increase in traffic avoiding the bridge
by taking a detour through Gloucestershire. In June a study for the Highways
Agency showed about 2,700 vehicles a day were doing this.
</TEXT>
