<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Adjudicator at Revenue to be Customs watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Elizabeth Filkin, the complaints adjudicator at the Inland Revenue, was
named yesterday as the new watchdog at Customs and Excise.
Ms Filkin will bring both departments under a new joint adjudicator's office
from April, although she will publish two annual reports setting out
complaints and recommendations.
Ms Valerie Strachan, who chairs Customs and Excise, said she was pleased
with its complaints procedures but 'recent surveys have indicated that there
is a strong case for external adjudication similar to that for the Revenue'.
She added: 'The benefits of such a system - increased confidence on the part
of the complainants and improved feedback for the department - are clear.'
New guidance leaflets are to be published and will be available at ports,
airports and local offices. The introduction of an independent element into
Customs' complaint handling does not limit the right to ask an MP to take a
case to the ombudsman.
Ms Filkin will deal with complaints about customs officers in the dealings
with the general public and businesses and also with delays in value added
tax repayments. In her annual report she will be able to recommend the
payment of compensation in some cases.
At the revenue Ms Filkin took up 308 cases for full investigation in her
first year. She settled 105 during the period, 65 wholly or partly in favour
of the complainant.
The government has issued figures showing that gains to income tax payers in
1995-96 are concentrated among the low-paid and the well-paid compared with
broadly comparable figures for 1987-88. Those paying more tax are
concentrated on those earning Pounds 15,000 to Pounds 50,000 a year.
Income tax payments for those earning between Pounds 50,000 and Pounds
70,000 are to be reduced by an average of Pounds 620. Those earning more
than Pounds 80,000 will benefit by Pounds 16,900 on average.
The figures were given in a written answer to Mr Clive Betts MP by Sir
George Young, financial secretary to the Treasury.
