<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Czechs set EU target dates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VINCENT BOLAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Czech Republic is to apply to join the European Union in 1996 and
expects to be a member by 1999, Mr Vaclav Klaus, prime minister, said
yesterday. Membership talks are expected to begin after the EU
inter-governmental conference in 1996 which is to set the ground rules and
timetable for membership for the countries of central and eastern Europe. Mr
Klaus said the government would establish a special committee on January 1
to oversee the application. His announcement is expected to give the
government a boost in the run-up to local elections being held on November
18 and 19.
The Czech Republic will join Poland and Hungary as the first post-communist
countries to be considered for membership. Hungary and Poland have already
applied. Mr Klaus has long argued that his country is in a position to join
now because of its advanced economic and political reforms. Slovakia, fourth
member of the so-called Visegrad group, is also likely to seek entry.
