<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Markets retreat after early rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Republican success in Tuesday's elections sparked a strong rally in the
dollar and US and European financial markets yesterday, as investors
anticipated that a more pro-business Congress would pursue policies to aid
growth and cut government spending.
However, US markets were unable to sustain their early gains and Wall Street
retreated amid concerns that conflict between President Bill Clinton and a
Republican Congress could undermine investor confidence in the economy and
the dollar.
The markets were also troubled by fears of rising US interest rates; most
analysts expect rates to be raised next week to slow economic growth and
restrain inflation.
Some analysts believe the poll results have important implications for
monetary policy. Mr Richard Hoey, chief economist at the investment fund
group Dreyfus, said: 'The Fed will be now more free to tighten as fast and
as much as it wants. It had been under pressure from Democrats in Congress,
and with the Republicans taking over both houses, the pressure against the
Fed will fall.'
The possibility that the Republican success could lead Mr Alan Greenspan,
the Fed chairman, to raise rates further and faster than the markets had
expected was behind some of the selling on US markets yesterday.
By the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average - which had jumped 38 points
in the opening minutes - had sunk back to 3,831.75 points, a gain of 1.01 on
the day. But the dollar kept its gains in New York, up about two pfennigs
against the D-Mark at DM1.52755, and at Y97.775.
European stock markets greeted the Republican victories with impressive
advances, but unlike Wall Street they kept most of their gains. London's
FT-SE 100 index closed up 35.8 at 3,099.6, while in Frankfurt the DAX index
rose 43.03 to 2,096.47.
Wall Street was concerned that discord between Congress and the White House
might lead to legislative gridlock, and that a hardline Republican
leadership could block progress on trade.
Mr Richard McCabe, chief market strategist at Merrill Lynch, said Wall
Street was debating 'whether Republican control of both houses leads to more
legislation that is good for the market, or whether it leads to more
deadlock'.
Mr Hoey said any positive effects from the elections would probably soon
fade. 'The stock market is left with all the same issues it had before, in
terms of the outlook for the economy and the possibility for more Fed
tightenings. The core issue is how much more will interest rates go up.'
Lex, Page 24
World stocks, Page 45
London market report, Page 48
Currencies, Page 38
</TEXT>
