<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / BSkyB in talks over ITN supplying news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Sky Broadcasting is negotiating to have its 24-hours-a-day
television news channel, Sky News, supplied under contract by Independent
Television News.
If the deal goes through it would re-create an effective BBC-ITN national
television news monopoly in the UK.
Talks are believed to be well advanced between the BSkyB satellite
television venture and ITN, the ITV television news organisation. They have
involved Mr Rupert Murdoch, chairman of News Corporation, Mr Michael Green,
chairman of ITN and of Carlton Communications, and Mr Sam Chisholm, the
BSkyB chief executive.
Mr Chisholm said last night: 'We have plenty of suitors who want to get
involved with us in a whole range of areas. ITN is but one.'
Sky News is broadcast across Europe on the Astra satellite and is available
to millions of viewers through satellite dishes and cable television
networks. ITN, which supplies television news to ITV and Channel 4, already
provides news programmes around the clock.
For both sides, there are strong incentives to strike a deal.
ITN is 90 per cent controlled by three groups - Carlton, which runs the
London weekday licence and the Midlands ITV licence, Granada, and Reuters,
the news and information group - and is ambitious to expand.
Mr Murdoch controls 50 per cent of BSkyB, a consortium in which Pearson,
owner of the Financial Times, has a significant stake. He is committed to
continuing to provide a 24-hour news channel as part of the Sky package of
satellite channels.
BSkyB has been trying for several years to find a less costly way of
providing the news channel, but past talks with the BBC and ITN had come to
nothing.
Sky News costs about Pounds 30m a year to run and has never made a profit.
It is believed that the deal on offer from ITN could save BSkyB about Pounds
7m-Pounds 8m a year.
It is understood that a deal will be agreed only if ITN can show that its
service will be better as well as cheaper. BSkyB would insist on retaining
the Sky News name and editorial control.
The talks come as BSkyB prepares for a stock exchange flotation. Although
the negotiations about news provision are not believed to be directly
related, an agreement would almost certainly be seen as positive for the
BSkyB float, which is expected next month.
Tuesday's announcement by the Independent Television Commission - that it is
deferring until the end of 1995 the need for ITN shareholders to reduce
their stakes to 20 per cent - was also probably a precondition for a deal.
One large newspaper group yesterday expressed anger that UK television was
being completely 'carved up'.
The individual ITV shareholders in ITN could continue to hold on to larger
stakes than the 20 per cent maximum specified in the 1990 Broadcasting Act,
yet newspapers were still prevented from holding more than 20 per cent of an
ITV franchise.
News Corp up 15%, Page 33
</TEXT>
