<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 94 / Clinton defiant on economy in wake of Republican triumph
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton yesterday answered the Republican party's most
sweeping mid-term election triumph in nearly 50 years by promising to block
opposition attempts to 'turn the clock back' to the economic policies of the
1980s.
Alternately reflective and combative at an afternoon press conference, the
president welcomed the offers of co-operation with the Democrat
administration from the new Republican leadership in both houses of
Congress. 'I ask them to join me in the centre of the public debate where
the best ideas must come.'
But, he said: 'I say to those who would use this election to turn us back .
. . I will do all in my power to keep anyone from jeopardising this economic
recovery by taking us back to the policies and exploding deficits that
failed us before.'
His analysis of the drubbing his party had taken, an adverse reflection of
his own leadership, was not that the American people disliked the specifics
of Democratic policies. 'They just don't like it when they see what we do up
here.'
Mr Robert Dole, about to become majority leader in the Senate, echoed these
sentiments. 'If we don't deliver, we'll be out of here too,' he said.
Congressman Newt Gingrich, Speaker-presumptive of the House, commented: 'Let
the '96 presidential campaign come in '96.'
Mr Gingrich said he would seek accommodation with the administration - on
greater budgetary control, tax credits for middle-income families and
welfare reform - before pressing ahead with the ideological elements in the
Republican manifesto so inimical to President Clinton.
In the same spirit, Mr Clinton called Mr Gingrich yesterday and, according
to reports from both sides, offered, and received, pledges not to let the
nation's government sink into gridlock.
Mr Leon Panetta, White House chief of staff, said he had also spoken to Mr
Gingrich on election night and extracted a pledge that the Republican 'would
work with us to try and get the Gatt treaty passed' when both houses of the
old Congress reconvene for votes at the turn of this month.
The 52-48 Senate majority won by Republicans at the polls swelled by one
when Senator Richard Shelby, the conservative Democrat from Alabama,
announced he was crossing the political aisle. Flanked by Senators Dole and
Phil Gramm, he said he was joining 'a party of hope for America' and leaving
'a party of dependency'.
The overall results, in which no Republican incumbent in Congress was
defeated, far exceeded the party's wildest dreams. But the Senate will have
to get along without a Republican candidate who would have been difficult to
imbue with any spirit of co-operation. Mr Oliver North lost in Virginia to
Senator Charles Robb, but ominously promised to return.
In California, Mr Michael Huffington, his pockets Dollars 25m (Pounds 15.2m)
lighter as a result of his campaign, had still not publicly conceded his
two-point defeat by Senator Dianne Feinstein, claiming that absentee ballots
could yet vote him in.
But these losses were more than offset by the cull of dozens of Democratic
luminaries.
The massacre leaves the country with a new political face. In the House,
with nine contests still undecided, the Republicans had a provisional net
gain of 49 and had already acquired an edge of about 227-198. The lone
independent and nominal socialist, Bernie Sanders of Vermont, survived.
