<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / US Mid-Term Elections (November 8): North defeated on
Virginia battlefield - Democrat Robb fends off challenge from former marine
colonel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A lonely ray of sunshine shone in Virginia for the battered Democrats in
yesterday's US congressional elections when Senator Chuck Robb held off the
challenge of Mr Oliver North, the controversial former marine colonel. Mr
North, loathed even by many in his own Republican party for his role in the
Iran-Contra affair, was the candidate to whom the Democrats would most have
hated to lose.
The Virginia victory, which sees Mr Robb re-elected, was scant consolation,
however. A string of losses in other states shook the Senate majority the
Democrats have held for the last eight years.
Although Mr North was found guilty of lying to Congress over his role in
arranging the exchange of weapons for the release of US hostages held in
Lebanon, while siphoning off money to arm the Nicaraguan Contra guerrillas
in defiance of a law passed by Congress, his conviction was voided on a
technicality.
He inspires almost fanatical loyalty among his core supporters, especially
those who classify themselves as belonging to the Christian right wing.
But he remains a distasteful figure to many Republicans, and especially to
loyalists of former President Ronald Reagan. Mrs Nancy Reagan denounced him
for his role in the Iran-Contra conspiracy, and for what he said about Mr
Reagan's role in it.
Virginia's other senator, Mr John Warner, although a Republican, said he did
not wish to serve in the Senate alongside a man who had lied to Congress.
But Mr Robb himself was so widely disliked by the voters, and campaigned so
weakly until the last few days, that he came close to handing the election
to a man who most politicians six months ago thought to be unelectable.
Once one of the Democrats' brightest stars and widely expected to be a
future presidential candidate, Mr Robb has struggled to live down stories
about his private life that have damaged the reputation he built up as one
of Virginia's most effective governors.
He may owe his winning margin to the two independent candidates who entered
the race. One, former Governor Douglas Wilder, withdrew and campaigned for
Mr Robb, helping him to reap around 88 per cent of the votes cast by black
Virginians.
Mr Marshall Coleman, an independent Republican backed by Senator Warner,
fought on, drawing votes away from the main candidates. But he won fewer
votes than opinion polls had projected.
</TEXT>
