<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Republicans poised to win Congress: Democrats face loss of
House for first time in 40 years - Dole predicts Senate victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Republican party stood on the brink of control of both houses of the US
Congress early today, administering a severe rebuff to President Bill
Clinton and the incumbent Democratic party.
Results and TV projections mostly from the eastern half of the country, but
including Arizona, pointed to a net Republican gain of seven seats in the
Senate, exactly what was what needed to overturn the 56-44 Democratic
majority.
Elsewhere a Republican candidate was trailing, but only slightly, in
Pennsylvania, a Democratic seat, and there was no result declared in
Minnesota, a possible Democratic gain. Altogether 35 Senate seats were at
stake.
Mr Robert Dole, Republican leader in the Senate, said cautiously: 'We're not
there yet, but I think we'll make it.' Senator John Breaux, the Lousiana
Democrat, virtually conceded defeat as he left a reception at the White
House with the words,'I've never been in the minority before.'
In the House of Representatives, in Democratic hands since 1954, a
late-evening projection by the Associated Press pointed to a net Republican
gain of 40 seats, again precisely what they need to reverse the current
Democratic edge of 256-178, with one independent.
The one overwhelming consolation for the Democrats was the defeat in the
Senate contest in Virginia of Mr Oliver North, architect of the Iran-Contra
scandals, by Senator Chuck Robb. With most of the votes counted, Mr Robb was
ahead by about 5 points, according to exit polls, winning mostly on the
strength of distrust of Mr North.
Some other Democratic warhorses survived, either easily (Senators Edward
Kennedy in Massachusetts, Paul Sarbanes in Maryland and Robert Byrd in West
Virginia) or with difficulty (Senator Frank Lautenberg in New Jersey). Also
withstanding strong Democratic challenges were Republican senators Bill Roth
in Delaware and James Jeffords in Vermont.
But the killing blows were delivered in southern border states, where the
Democrats lost both seats in Tennessee, including that of Senator Jim Sasser
to Dr Bill Frist, a political novice, and in Oklahoma, where the well-known
congressman Dave McCurdy was crushed by Congressman Jim Inhofe. Earlier
Republican Senate pick-ups in Ohio, Maine and Michigan had been freely
predicted,
The Republicans also began to pick up some of the 22 Democratic
governorships of the 36 being contested, with victories in Oklahoma, Kansas,
Wyoming and Tennessee, though the loss of South Carolina looked likely.
In Maryland, another Democratic seat, Mr Parris Glendening was falling
behind Mrs Ellen Sauerbrey, the conservative Republican. But in Georgia,
Governor Zell Miller was holding on to an edge over another
arch-conservative, Mr Guy Millner.
Results in the two big states - California and New York - were expected
later, though Governor Mario Cuomo in the latter was behind Mr George Pataki
in very early returns. Of former President George Bush's two sons, George W
Jr was leading Governor Ann Richards in Texas, but Jeb was narrowly behind
Governor Lawton Chiles in Florida.
But both were faring better than Mr Hugh Rodham, brother of the First Lady.
He was thrashed for the US Senate seat in Florida by Mr Connie Mack, the
Republican incumbent.
One of the more startling upsets was still just possible in Washington, DC,
late last night. Mr Marion Barry, a three-time mayor seeking rehabilitation
after a narcotics conviction was barely ahead of Mrs Carol Schwartz, the
Republican, in spite of the fact that Democrats and blacks both have vast
majorities in the nation's capital.
Oliver North defeated on Virginia battlefield, Page 5
Observer Page 23;
Bonds Page 34;
Currencies Page 36;
US stocks Page 43;
London stocks Page 46
