<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stock index futures mostly marked time in line with the cash market,
drifting slightly higher in continued low trading volume, writes Jeffrey
Brown.
There were 10,862 contracts, up from 8,091 on Monday. But some 2,000 of this
was spread trading as investors moved from the December to the March
contract, so underlying volume was little changed.
At the official 4.10pm close the FT-SE 100 December contract had clawed back
above the 3,070 critical chart level to end at 3,072, up 11 points. The
premium to the cash market was 10 points, with fair value around 7.5 points.
There was some excitment in the early morning when the market appeared to
take a serious run at cash equities on the back of rumours of an imminent
rise for base rates. But this fizzled out by mid-morning and the session
took on a slightly unreal atmosphere with very little business being done
either way.
However, sentiment picked up towards the close, with Wall Street showing
signs of a strong rally, and traders were hopeful of continued upward
momemtum today.
Turnover in traded options rose to 28,478 lots after 21,113 on Monday. FT-SE
and Euro FT-SE business totalled 16,500 lots. Lonrho stood out among
individual stock options with 4,230 dealt. Cable and Wireless and ICI were
active.
