<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries higher after strong auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN and CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury prices edged higher yesterday after a relatively strong auction
of three-year notes demonstrated solid demand for new paper. Activity was
moderate as traders awaited news on US elections and a producer price report
due on Thursday.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year bond was up  7/16 at 93 1/16 yielding
8.114 per cent and the two-year note up  1/16 at 99 23/32 , to yield 7.011
per cent.
Early in the day prices were steady on trader fears of low demand for the
medium-term notes, but by midday prices had climbed moderately as sentiment
turned positive ahead of the 1pm auction.
Analysts expect a 0.1 per cent rise in the producer price index for October.
A bigger increase could trigger fears of a large or early interest rate
increase by the Fed.
The markets watched for election news but with little consensus on their
impact. Mr Robert Brusca of Nikko Securities in New York, said markets could
be buoyed if Republicans make significant gains in both houses of the
legislature.
Also overshadowing markets was the increase in interest rates widely
expected from next Tuesday's meeting of the Federal Reserve's open market
committee.
European government bonds ended another calm session slightly firmer,
supported by buoyant German bunds and firmer US Treasuries.
However, volume has dwindled sharply and traders said investor flows were
few and far between. 'A lot of people have in effect shut their books for
the year,' said one analyst.
German bunds recouped early losses to end nearly  1/2 point higher,
underpinned by firm demand for the first tranche of the government's latest
10-year issue.
Although demand for the paper was said to be subdued, dealers reported keen
interest from several banks, some of which were buying bonds to cover short
positions they had established prior to the sale.
The Bundesbank allotted DM3bn of the 7.5 per cent paper to the federal bond
consortium at 99.75, yielding 7.54 per cent. A further DM3bn to DM4bn of the
bonds are expected to be sold at today's auction; together with the
Bundesbank's market tending allotment, the issue is expected to total
DM10bn.
Earlier in the day, bunds were depressed by news of a larger than expected
drop in the October jobless rate, but shrugged off a small upward revision
in the September M3 money supply growth rate. The December bund future on
DTB closed at 89.41, up 0.41.
UK gilts rose on the back of firmer European and US bonds, with little in
the way of news or capital flows to drive prices.
'Until the FOMC meeting (on November 15), it's likely to remain pretty
trendless,' said one dealer. After that, market participants will turn their
attention to the Budget on November 29. 'We often have a slight bull run up
to the Budget because everyone hopes they'll do the right thing,' he added.
The December long gilt futures contract rose by  13/32 to 101 3/32 .
Swedish bonds clawed back some of their recent sharp losses, with the yield
on the 11-year benchmark falling by 8 basis points to 11.57 per cent.
However, the market is likely to remain jittery and volatile ahead of
Sunday's referendum on European Union membership.
</TEXT>
