<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / M&amp;S sees sales in Europe rise 20%: UK retailer plans
continental expansion as pre-tax profits rise 15% to Pounds 354m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Marks and Spencer, the food and clothing retailer, has lifted continental
European sales by 20 per cent since exporting its Outstanding Value Campaign
from the UK. The campaign, run in the UK for the past couple of years,
passes on to customers cost savings made through improvements in efficiency
and information technology without damaging operating margins. It is
operated jointly with suppliers, who benefit from higher production runs.
Sir Richard Greenbury, chairman, yesterday stressed that it was a long-term
project to improve and sharpen the products on sale.
Sales in Europe rose from Pounds 134.5m to Pounds 152.3m in the six months
to October 1, the group said yesterday. Operating profits were down from
Pounds 9.3m to Pounds 5m after charging Pounds 3.8m for the opening of new
stores.
Sir Richard said Europe had been through 'a very, very tough period, with
the consumer in the trenches. But if we can keep sales going at 20 per cent,
it will come through strongly in the second half.'
Total group pre-tax profits were 15 per cent ahead at Pounds 354.2m on the
back of a 6.9 per cent sales rise to Pounds 3.07bn.
M&amp;S is accelerating its expansion plans, and is lifting capital expenditure
to a record Pounds 400m this year. While most of this will be spent in the
UK, Sir Richard says there are few high streets and out-of-town sites where
the group has no store.
In contrast, there are only 25 stores on continental Europe. M&amp;S has already
identified a further 45 to 50 sites across France, Holland and Spain, but
Sir Richard stressed that the group would proceed with caution.
It had taken four years to find and negotiate an appropriate site before
opening the Valencia store last year.
'Our continued expansion is geared to the right sites and the speed at which
we can get them,' said Sir Richard. 'It's a marathon, not a sprint.'
The group is also looking at Japan and China following the success of its
Hong Kong operations, which are yielding better returns than anywhere else.
Operating profits in the Far East rose from Pounds 5.1m to Pounds 8m in the
half, while sales were up from Pounds 23.2m to Pounds 32.1m.
Sir Richard said a decision on whether to go ahead with its first store in
Japan would be taken within the next 12 months.
Lex, Page 24;
Details, Page 28
</TEXT>
