<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / The Lex Column: Waiting for take-off
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BA's second-quarter figures were so good that for a moment the market could
almost forget the continuing headache that is USAir. BA's stern cost control
was again in evidence and the strong growth in business traffic brought a
healthy increase in overall passenger yields. Year on year growth is bound
to slow now, if only because the business traffic recovery started in the
third quarter of BA's last financial year. But BA still has plenty of
momentum behind it and there are even signs that tariffs are firming.
It is the size of the final bill for BA's international expansion that is
the worry. Losses from France and Germany were unchanged in the first half
as the flag carriers attacked BA's Trojan horses. But it is USAir which is
the immediate concern. The Dollars 500m of cost reductions being asked of
the unions would barely offset its current losses and as the negotiations
grind on its low-cost rivals are leaving it further behind. The real fear is
not that BA will have to write off the Pounds 260m value of its stake, which
it could handle comfortably. It is that USAir will slowly die, threatening
the Pounds 70m of benefit BA expects this year, or that BA will feel
compelled to pour more money in to keep it alive.
The loss of Pounds 8m in preference dividends will be the only pain BA will
suffer from USAir in the current year which should see group profits jump by
over 40 per cent to around Pounds 430m. With the shares trading on about
11.5 times prospective earnings, it is hard to argue that they are
expensive. But until there is better news from USAir they are likely to
remain grounded.
</TEXT>
