<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Company fined over missing trade statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Intrastat, the system for collecting trade statistics among European Union
countries, has acquired teeth.
This week magistrates in Southend-on-Sea, Essex, fined Dams International, a
furniture dealer based in Liverpool, a total of Pounds 11,550, including
Pounds 300 costs, after it pleaded guilty to failing to supply Customs and
Excise with information on goods acquired from and supplied to EU countries.
Dams, which has annual turnover of about Pounds 12m and exports of Pounds
1.5m to the EU, is the first UK company to be prosecuted for failing to
supply statistics under the system introduced in January last year to
provide trade figures in the European single market.
It is one of 31,000 businesses registered for value added tax with annual EU
trade of more than Pounds 140,000 that are required to supply data on
so-called supplementary declarations.
These forms, which must be sent to Customs within 10 working days of the end
of the month, oblige companies to fill in nine boxes on each type of goods
traded. They provide 97.5 per cent of the statistics for Intrastat.
The remaining 2.5 per cent are drawn from smaller VAT-registered businesses
which have to complete two boxes on their VAT returns showing the value of
goods supplied to and acquired from EU countries. According to Customs and
Excise this is the only contribution that 150,000 companies make to the
compilation of national statistics.
Customs and Excise is generally satisfied with the level of compliance of UK
companies. Fewer than 200 cases of non-compliant traders are under
consideration.
But this case is a sign that the agency is prepared to take recalcitrants to
court when all other means of persuasion have failed.
Customs acted after Dams failed to supply monthly details from January 1993.
The officials made a compliance visit in July last year, sent a warning
letter in November and another warning letter by recorded delivery in
January. In March a prosecuting officer interviewed company officials under
caution.
Customs and Excise offered the company a 'compound penalty' of Pounds 3,450.
This is an administrative fine, offered to all first offenders in lieu of
court proceedings, and has been used to settle with about 10 offending
companies. Dams paid the penalty, started to produce monthly returns for
Intrastat, but failed to produce 16 missing monthly returns.
Customs decided to prosecute as a last resort. After Dams produced one of
the missing declarations the company was charged with 15 offences of failing
to provide the information. It pleaded guilty to Southend magistrates on
Monday and was fined Pounds 750 per offence, compared with maximum possible
fine of Pounds 2,500.
Mr Paul Nelson, Dams' company secretary, said problems with the computer
system caused the failure to comply with the Intrastat rules. He was having
to work through 2,000 invoices a month to complete the forms and the job was
too time-consuming.
The case has puzzled Customs officers, however. Officials say the Intrastat
system is less burdensome than the declarations that were previously
required. The net annual saving to UK businesses of the new system has been
estimated at Pounds 135m.
The high level of compliance has increased official confidence that the
figures give an accurate picture of Britain's trade with the EU.
</TEXT>
