<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Life is not yet a beach for business leaders: Roderick Oram
finds delegates uneasy in spite of the more benign climate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rather than basking in the most benign economic climate for years, business
is worrying that the government could turn the recovery into a wash out
before the next election.
Delegates to the CBI's annual conference were also concerned that rising
output and low inflation had failed to solve some of business's most
persistent problems such as lack of finance.
Business is also having to cope with some new difficulties. The most
pressing is how to persuade customers to accept price increases to cover
higher raw-material costs.
Mr Simon Eccleston, chief executive of Trans-Tech Industries, said: 'I'm
scared something will go wrong again.' The west Midlands manufacturer of
automation equipment has survived the recession, but, added Mr Eccleston:
'We have to trust politicians but now we can all see through them.'
Mr John McKeown, a director of Allied Domecq and managing director of the
Tetley Pub Company, said its pubs across the country have seen a slow
improvement in business over the past six months. The future is now
promising, 'provided someone doesn't over-correct near the next election'.
Mr Ernest Kidney, managing director of Balcas, said: 'We need continuing
stability, not just for a few years but longer-term.' His Ulster-based wood
processor depends on the rest of Britain for some 85 per cent of its sales
in construction, packaging and other fields.
Calls for government policy action ranged widely across fields from
transport and environment to training and education. Business also pressed
for more effort from the government on European integration.
The dominant theme, however, was that industry could solve many of its
problems through its own investment, but only if the government made tax
changes to encourage the process. The CBI has made capital allowances and
similar measures the central plank of its Budget submission.
The need to spend more on infrastructure, particularly transport, was a
concern expressed by business leaders from diverse industries. Mr Pat Lee,
development director of Wincanton, a distribution company based in
Wincanton, Somerset, said the south-west, for example, was ill-served by its
transportation links.
Many delegates welcomed private finance of infrastructure projects, an
approach reaffirmed by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, at the conference
yesterday. Some Pounds 500m of private sector funding will have flowed into
transport projects this year, he said.
Mr Ivor Warburton, managing director of the West Coast Line, said securing
such funding was the key to rebuilding the railways. He said: 'It's a race
to do it before we get caught in a downward quality spiral' as existing
equipment wears out.
The pressure to invest in infrastructure and other capital equipment appears
to be building rapidly judging by the brisk rate of growth across the
spectrum of economic activity. Inevitably, of course, a few areas are
struggling. Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, said: 'It wouldn't be
much fun standing on a doorstep trying to sell pensions.'
Two barometers - train trips and packing cases - give a guide to the breadth
of the upturn. Mr Warburton said leisure travel on the West Coast Line began
to grow at the turn of the year and business travel in March. Mr Kidney of
Balcas said demand for packing cases, flat for the past two years, began to
recover about three to six months ago.
Mr Bill Good of Sterling Tubes, which supplies seamless stainless steel
tubes for process industries, said: 'Business is recovering but margins are
tight and I'm worried about unfair competition (from foreign suppliers).'
Of the few clouds gathering on the economic horizon, it is rising prices and
lack of finance which appear to worry business leaders most. With paper
costs up 30 per cent over the past year, for example, it has been hard for
Kenrick &amp; Jefferson, a large printer based in the west Midlands to pass them
on to customers used to unchanged prices over recent years.
Mr Stephen Adams, a divisional director of the company, said: 'It could be
easier next year when people have built them into their budgets.'
Mr Peter Pring, director of corporate affairs of 3M UK, said: 'We're a
little concerned with the trend of raw material prices.' It has, however,
managed to keep in check the prices of its 60,000 products across a range of
markets from consumer to healthcare and industrial.
Mr Eccleston of Trans-Tech, which makes of automation equipment, said:
'Demand is marvellous, but we can't do some of the business because we can't
finance it.'
He believes that it is a widespread problem, judging by his experience as a
board member of Walsall's Training and Enterprise Council. 'Of 1,500
companies the Tec ran a health check on, over half were concerned about a
lack of funding,' he said.
His unhappiness was echoed by several other delegates who, although they
were satisfied by the general state of the economy and their business, were
heading back to work to tackle this and other lingering problems.
</TEXT>
