<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / CBI cool on union chief's training call: Bill Jordan warns
conference of complacent attitudes - BP chief underlines the 'competitive
realities'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Industrial companies should pay a training levy if the UK is to overcome the
handicap of the least skilled workforce in Europe, Mr Bill Jordan, president
of the AEEU craft union, told the CBI conference in Birmingham yesterday.
He said the voluntary approach to training had been found wanting, and
added: 'If the CBI is serious about wanting a strategy to deliver skills for
the next century, we should not be debating whether to have a training levy
but tailoring the shape of one.'
He said budgets to improve skills had been cut by 35 per cent in the past
five years. It was 'dangerously complacent' to praise Britain's best
companies when the nation was lagging on productivity by up to 40 per cent
compared with overseas rivals.
The CBI responded cautiously to the idea. Mr Dominic Cadbury, chairman of
Cadbury Schweppes and the CBI's education committee, said: 'The CBI has not
supported the concept in the past but we will be asking our members to
express their views and we will be consulting all members via the regional
councils.'
But Mr Jordan's argument sparked criticism from some delegates to the
conference. Mr John Phillips, chairman of Reliance-Barker-Davies, the
engineering group, dismissed the idea of a levy as 'simply an additional
payroll tax' and 'a pure addition to costs, a deterrent to employment'.
Earlier, Mr David Simon, chief executive of BP, had warned that even
well-trained employees faced uncertainty. He said: 'We will not be thanked
by future generations if we duck the competitive realities of the present.'
Jobs for life were unlikely. 'I think most of us recognise that such a
prospect is no longer wholly appropriate,' he suggested.
Ms Kamlesh Bahl, who chairs the Equal Opportunities Commission, told the CBI
that inequality was 'demonstrably inefficient' and that 'a workforce trained
in a discriminatory way is inflexible'.
She noted that there had been a sevenfold increase in compensation over the
past year since the ceiling on awards had been abolished last year. In cases
of sexual harassment, awards against transgressing companies were likely to
increase.
But Ms Bahl, seeking to head off any criticism that the Equal Opportunities
Commission was a hindrance to companies' freedom of action, assured
businessmen that 'this is not a battle of the sexes'. Rather, the fair
management of human resources was 'about achieving competitiveness through
equality of opportunity'.
</TEXT>
