FT  09 NOV 94 / Ashdown urges end to donations to Tories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown, leader of the Liberal Democrats, yesterday sought to
exploit the disillusionment of businesspeople with the government by asking
companies to stop making political donations to the Conservative party.
Repeating a thought which has been expressed privately by many
industrialists, Mr Ashdown said: 'I do not believe you can say any longer
that this is a government which has been good for business.'
Mr Ashdown said at the CBI conference: 'Just as the TUC is beginning to
recognise that too close a link to one political party is not necessarily in
their interest, I hope that Britain's business community will begin to
reassess the extent to which unquestioning support, including financial
support, for the Conservative party is in their interest.'
Seeking to tap the sentiments in favour of strengthening the European Union,
manifest in CBI polls published earlier this week, Mr Ashdown urged the
business community to speak up for its own interests.
He said: 'It will be disastrous for Britain and business if we are excluded
from a single currency. And if that's what you believe too, it's time to be
saying it loud and clear.'
