<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Blair pledges union reforms will be kept
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair yesterday promised business leaders that Labour would retain
the government's central trade union reforms and would consult
industrialists before introducing a minimum wage.
Speaking to senior executives at the Per Cent Club, which organises
charitable activity, Mr Blair said: 'We are not in the business of sweeping
away the trade union and labour relations laws of the 1980s.'
His comments coincided with a blunt warning by Mr Roy Hattersley, a former
Labour deputy leader, that the party must consider breaking its links with
the trade union movement if it wants to win the next general election.
Giving the George Orwell lecture at Birkbeck College, London, Mr Hattersley
said victory was possible only if Labour became a party of ideas rather than
vested interests.
He said: 'It is difficult to pursue truth wherever it may lead if two or
three mighty unions, which dominate the policy debate, have decided which
way to vote before the discussion begins.'
Mr Blair, setting out the framework for a working relationship between
business and a Labour government, offered strong support for a dynamic
market economy, and rejected the tax-and-spend approach of the last Labour
government.
He said strike ballots, union elections and curbs on mass picketing were
'here to stay', and ruled out any return to high marginal tax rates.
Mr Blair said the minimum wage would be introduced 'so as to avoid any
adverse impact on jobs', suggesting that the level would be lower than the
rate of more than Pounds 4 an hour sought by influential union leaders.
Mr Blair also spoke of the 'interdependence of business and the community'.
The club, he said, was a recognition by business that it had a
responsibility to wider society.
Business involvement in the community was more than an act of charity. 'Our
communities are your customers, and communities are your employees. The
state of society beyond the factory gate, the shop window and the office
entrance matters to business.'
Mr Blair supported the idea of a national youth and community service
scheme.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, will today publish plans to reform the
tax system by toughening inheritance tax rules, simplifying corpora-tion tax
and collecting unpaid tax.
</TEXT>
