<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Lloyd's to chase frozen deposit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's of London last night threatened legal proceedings against the
Alliance &amp; Leicester building society if it did not agree to release funds
held on behalf of a member of the insurance market.
The Alliance &amp; Leicester confirmed that its Isle of Man office had frozen an
account belonging to a Lloyd's Name.
It said it had received 'notice' from a firm of solicitors that the funds,
which acted as a deposit at Lloyd's, 'are subject of a fraud'.
Lossmaking Names hailed the case as a victory in their battle to prevent
Lloyd's seizing money held on their behalf to settle debts at the insurance
market. It is believed to be the first time a UK financial institution has
agreed to freeze a Name's funds in this way.
But Lloyd's insisted that the allegations on which the Alliance &amp; Leicester
appeared to have acted 'are similar to those raised in a previous court
action against Lloyd's which, on Lloyd's application, were struck out'.
A group formed to protect the interests of the wealthiest Lloyd's Names met
for the first time yesterday. The High Premium Group, which has 285 members,
is a response to reforms introducing new forms of corporate capital.
</TEXT>
