<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Subsidy urged for 'green' power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many types of renewable energy are too expensive to qualify for subsidies,
the industry regulator has warned.
Professor Stephen Littlechild said the government should choose the cheapest
forms of 'green' power for its forthcoming round of subsidies rather than
try to promote particular technologies.
This would mean dropping hydro schemes and projects which burn agricultural
and forestry waste, or energy crops such as coppicing. He also warned that
combined heat and power schemes would add extra costs. Instead, emphasis
should be given to wind, landfill gas and waste combust-ion.
Prof Littlechild's advice comes as ministers are finalising a new round of
subsidies for 'green' energy projects. They intend to choose about
300MW-400MW of schemes which will be allowed to charge premium prices for
their electricity.
Ministers have said they will put bidding projects into various technology
'bands' and select those that look most promising. Prof Littlechild
challenges this approach because it would lead to expensive projects
qualifying.
Instead, he says, ministers should select the 70 cheapest projects out of
the 520 submitted. This would ensure that prices would be 30 per cent below
the last subsidy round in 1991, although even these would be 50 per cent
above long-run free-market prices and will require a subsidy of Pounds 400m
over 15 to 20 years.
Prof Littlechild's report provoked a sharp response from the renewables
industry, which is trying to promote a wide range of technologies.
The Department of Trade and Industry, which is vetting the bids, said that
it had taken note of Prof Littlechild's report. Ministers hope to announce
the new subsidies next month.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
