<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Wakeham set to head press body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Wakeham, the former leader of the House of Lords, has emerged as
favourite to succeed Lord McGregor as chairman of the Press Complaints
Commission.
Lord McGregor, who is 73, is expected to retire from the newspaper and
magazine industry's self-regulation body early next year although his
contract runs to the end of next year. The exact timing of his departure has
not yet been decided.
The Press Standards Board of Finance, which has the task of finding a new
chairman for the commission, has been using Spencer Stuart, the executive
search group.
Lord Wakeham, who left the government in the July reshuffle, was top of the
list submitted by the headhunters. A formal decision is expected later this
week.
However, recent tension between the press and the government over
allegations of 'sleaze' has raised concern about the wisdom of appointing a
former senior Conservative politician to the sensitive post.
But those who argue that Lord Wakeham's political connections might be
valuable in managing the often turbulent relations between press and
politicians - and the possibility of press legislation - are likely to be in
the majority.
Lord Wakeham is seen as having an open mind on the press and has in the past
restrained those most keen on statutory intervention on press standards.
If Lord Wakeham is not chosen, or does not want the job, the most likely
successor to Lord McGregor would probably be Professor Robert Pinker, the
commission's privacy commissioner.
</TEXT>
