<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 94 / Ministry 'may cut 30% of jobs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Up to 30 per cent of 11,000 jobs at the Ministry of Agriculture may be cut
over the next two to three years, the IPMS civil service union said
yesterday.
The cuts, part of a government review of civil service staff levels, begin
with at least 550 jobs due to go by next March.
The initial reduction of at least 5 per cent, designed to cut running costs,
is due to take effect through early retirement.
But Mr David Luxton, IPMS national officer for agriculture, said fewer than
half the 630 staff invited to apply were believed to have done so by this
week's deadline. Only those aged over 50 in middle management grades and
above have been asked to seek early retirement.
'Our fear is that we will move towards compulsory redundancies next year,'
he said. Compulsory redundancies were introduced at the ministry for the
first time in June, with 64 consultancy jobs lost at Adas, the advisory
agency being privatised, he said.
The IPMS, which represents about 3,000 senior and specialist staff at the
ministry, said it was expecting more staff cuts as a result of a review of
senior grades and a review of all aspects of ministry spending, both ordered
by the Treasury.
Mr Luxton said the senior staff review was modelled on that of the Treasury,
which announced last month that about one in four senior jobs would go.
The agriculture jobs targeted would mainly be those of advisers on the rural
economy, food production and safety, and animal welfare.
Mr Luxton warned that the 'arbitrary' cuts in staff numbers would lead to
delays and a deterioration in services to farmers.
</TEXT>
