FT  09 NOV 94 / Mozambique peace urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MAPUTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A South African delegation yesterday met Mozambique's President Joaquim
Chissano and the leader of the former rebel movement Renamo to urge peaceful
transition to democratic government after multi-party elections more than a
week ago. This follows warnings by Renamo leader Afonso Dhlakama that he may
not recognise the poll results, due next week.
Partial results, released yesterday, showed Mr Chissano and his ruling party
well ahead of his challengers. In the presidential race, Mr Chissano had 62
per cent of the vote at more than 2,000 of the 7,444 polling stations,
compared with 26 per cent for Mr Dhlakama. In the vote for parliament, Mr
Chissano's Frelimo led with 52 per cent, compared with Mr Dhlakama's Renamo
on 30 per cent. The possibility of renewed violence, which racked the
country for 16 years, worries Mozambique's neighbours. The South African
delegation included Defence Minister Joe Modise, Security Minister Sidney
Mufamadi and Mr Aziz Pahad, deputy foreign minister.
